Fill and boil your #kettle{}.

Roughly chop the @hazelnuts{25}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the hazelnuts and @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} and dry-fry, stirring
regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Once toasted, transfer to a #small bowl{} and set aside.

Pour the boiled water into a #large saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the pasta.

Add the @linguine{180%g} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until
tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{}
and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Roughly chop the @chives{1} (or use #scissors{} if easier).

Pop the (now empty) #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the @onion marmalade{40%g} and garlic and stir-fry for
~{1%minute}.

Stir the @water for the sauce{100%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g} into the
pan.

Bring the mixture to a boil, then turn the heat down slightly and simmer until
reduced by half, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once the sauce has reduced, add the @creme fraiche{150%g}, @peas{120%g} and a
good grind of @pepper{}. Stir until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir the cooked linguine, @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and half the
chives into the sauce. Mix well to combine.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if it looks a little dry.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Share the creamy pasta between your #bowls{}.

Spoon the hazelnut crumb over the top.

Finish with a scattering of the remaining chives. Enjoy!